# Identified Issues & Fixes for `fetchAll`
---
## 🐛 Specific Bugs & Security/Performance Problems
### 1. Sequential Request Execution (Performance Bottleneck)
The `for...of` loop uses `await` inside the iteration, so each fetch and JSON parse operation **must complete before the next URL is processed**. For batches of URLs, this drastically increases total runtime: total time equals the sum of individual request times, instead of the duration of the single slowest request when run in parallel.

### 2. Unchecked HTTP Response Success
The code does not validate that the HTTP response was successful via `response.ok`. This causes:
- Error status codes (4xx/5xx) are treated as valid successful requests
- Error payloads (e.g., `{"error": "Not Found"}` from failed APIs) are added to the results array as if they are valid data
- Calling `res.json()` on non-JSON error bodies will throw an unhandled crash

### 3. No Per-Request Error Handling
Any network failure, invalid JSON response, or timed-out request will crash the entire `fetchAll` function with no graceful recovery. There is no way to handle individual failed URLs without breaking the entire batch.

### 4. No Built-In Request Timeouts
The native `fetch` API has no default timeout, so a stalled or unresponsive server will hang the function indefinitely, blocking the caller's event loop.

### 5. Hidden Resource Leaks
If `res.json()` throws an error, the response stream is not explicitly canceled, though modern runtimes will eventually clean this up, it is best practice to abort unused streams to free up resources early.

---
## ✅ Improved Implementations
Below are two production-ready fixes tailored to common use cases:

---
### Variant 1: Fail-Fast (Matches Original Behavior, But Improved)
This version retains the original "fail entire batch on any error" logic, but adds parallel execution, timeouts, and proper response validation:
```javascript
async function fetchAll(urls) {
  // Create parallel fetch promises for all URLs
  const fetchPromises = urls.map(async (url) => {
    // Add 10-second timeout to each request to avoid hanging
    const abortController = new AbortController();
    const requestTimeout = setTimeout(() => abortController.abort(), 10000);

    try {
      const response = await fetch(url, { signal: abortController.signal });

      // Reject explicitly for non-success HTTP status codes
      if (!response.ok) {
        throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}: Failed to fetch ${url}`);
      }

      // Only parse JSON for valid successful responses
      return await response.json();
    } finally {
      // Clean up timeout to prevent memory leaks
      clearTimeout(requestTimeout);
    }
  });

  // Preserve input URL order and resolve all parallel requests
  return Promise.all(fetchPromises);
}
```

